naments]]\n|list1=\n{{navboxes|title=[[List of Grand Slam women's singles champions|Women's singles]]\n|list1=\n{{Australian Open women's singles champions}}\n{{French Open women's singles champions}}\n{{Wimbledon women's singles champions}}\n{{US Open women's singles champions}}\n}}\n{{navboxes|title=[[List of Grand Slam women's doubles champions|Women's doubles]]\n|list1=\n{{Australian Open women's doubles champions}}\n{{French Open women's doubles champions}}\n{{Wimbledon women's doubles champions}}\n{{US Open women's doubles champions}}\n}}\n{{navboxes|title=[[List of Grand Slam mixed doubles champions|Mixed doubles]]\n|list1=\n{{Wimbledon mixed doubles champions}}\n{{US Open mixed doubles champions}}\n}}\n{{navboxes|title=Others\n|list1=\n{{Tennis Career Grand Slam Champions}}\n{{Women's tennis players who won two or more Grand Slam singles titles in one calendar year}}\n}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Serena Williams tennis seasons|2]]\n[[Category:2013 tennis player seasons|Williams tennis season]]\n[[Category:2013 in American tennis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{infobox tennis player season 2\n|image=Serena Williams BNP Paribas Showdown.jpg\n|caption=Williams at the BNP Paribas Showdown\n|image_size=275px\n|fullname= Serena Jameka Williams\n|country={{flagu|United States}}\n|calendarprizemoney = $12,385,572\n|singlesrecord = {{tennis record|won=78|lost=4}}\n|singlestitles = 11\n|yearendsinglesranking = No. 1\n|currentsinglesranking = \n|singlesrankingchange = {{increase}} 2\n|AustralianOpenresult = QF\n|FrenchOpenresult = '''[[2013 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|W]]'''\n|Wimbledonresult = 4R\n|USOpenresult = '''[[2013 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|W]]'''\n|Othertournaments = <!-- adds a \"Other tournaments\" title -->\n|MastersCupresult = '''W'''\n|Olympicsresult = \n|doublesrecord = {{tennis record|won=7|lost=3}}\n|doublestitles = \n|yearenddoublesranking =No. 64\n|currentdoublesranking =\n|doublesrankingchange = {{decrease}} 30\n|grandslamsdoublesresults = \n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult = QF\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult =\n|WimbledonDoublesresult = \n|USOpenDoublesresult = SF\n|OthertournamentsDoubles = <!-- adds a \"Other doubles tournaments\" title -->\n|MastersCupDoublesresult =\n|OlympicsDoublesresult = \n|mixedrecord =\n|mixedtitles =\n|AustralianOpenMixedresult =\n|FrenchOpenMixedresult = \n|WimbledonMixedresult =\n|USOpenMixedresult =\n|OthertournamentsMixedDoubles =\n|OlympicMixedDoublesresult =\n|Fedcup = \n|Fedcupresult =\n|Injury = <!-- add injuries with date/interval, type of injury in brackets and reference if available -->\n|Notes = <!-- general important notes and/or anything that has changed from previous season: change of coach, equipment, ...etc -->\n|updated = 28 October 2013\n}}\n{{Main|Serena Williams}}\nThe '''2013 Serena Williams tennis season''' officially began on 30 December with the start of the [[2013 WTA Tour]], and follows on from a 12-match winning streak which began at the end of the [[2012 Serena Williams tennis season|2012 Season]]. Williams produced the most consistent season in her career reaching 13 finals and winning 11 titles, the most since 12 titles from [[Martina Hingis]] in 1997. She also won her second [[2013 French Open|French Open]], her first since 2002, as well as her fifth [[2013 US Open (tennis)|US Open]]. She also dominated the clay season winning 5 titles and having a 28-0 record on the surface and produced her longest winning streak at 34. Williams also had the best winning percentage of 95.1%, the highest since 1990 and became the first women's player to eclipse the $10 million mark at $12,385,572, beating the previous single-season prize money record of $7.9 million set in 2012 by [[Victoria Azarenka]].<ref>{{cite web|work=Forbes|title=Serena Williams Finishes Historic $12.4 Million Tennis Season With Another Title|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kurtbadenhausen/2013/10/27/serena-williams-finishes-historic-12-4-million-tennis-season-with-another-title/|date=27 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Bleacher|title=Serena Williams Wraps Up Her Best Season Ever, and She's Only Getting Better|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1828528-serena-williams-wraps-up-her-best-season-ever-and-shes-only-getting-better|date=28 October 2013}}</ref> Williams finished the year at no. 1, this the third time that Williams ended as the number 1 player in the year. Based on her performance in 2013, she was named 'World Champion' for the fourth time and the second time in a row.\n\n==Year in detail==\n\n===Early hard court season and Australian Open===\n\n====Brisbane International====\nWilliams began her 2013 campaign at the [[2013 Brisbane International|Brisbane International]]. In her first match, she faced compatriot and second-ranked American [[Varvara Lepchenko]] and won in straight sets in 59 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena cruises by Lepchenko in Brisbane|url=http://www.tennis.com/news/2012/12/serena-cruises-lepchenko-brisbane/45791/|date=30 December 2012}}</ref> In the second round, she faced Frenchwoman [[Aliz\u00e9 Cornet]] and took the match, winning both sets at two in exactly an hour with the help of 6 aces.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Williams blasts through to quarterfinals|url=http://www.brisbaneinternational.com.au/2013/01/williams-first-through-to-quarterfinals|date=1 January 2013}}</ref> In the quarterfinals, Williams faced another American in [[Sloane Stephens]] and defeated her younger foe, breaking Stephens once in each set, while holding her serve at each time.<ref>{{cite web|work=LA Times|title=Williams defeats Sloane Stephens to reach semifinal round.|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/03/sports/la-sp-newswire-20130104|date=3 January 2013}}</ref> In the semifinals Williams was bound to face world no. 1 [[Victoria Azarenka]]; however, the Belarusian withdrew before the match with a toe injury, giving Williams a free bye into the final.<ref>{{cite web|work=Brisbane International|title=Azarenka withdraws due to toe injury|url=http://www.brisbaneinternational.com.au/2013/01/azarenka-withdraws-due-to-toe-injury|date=4 January 2013}}</ref> In the final, Williams faced Russian [[Anastasia Pavlyuchenkova]]; the match started with holds in the first four games but Williams then took seven games in a row before Pavlyuchenkova took another game. Williams then closed out the match, losing only three games.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Williams blasts through women's final|url=http://www.brisbaneinternational.com.au/2013/01/williams-blasts-through-womens-final|date=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Australian Open====\nWilliams came into the [[2013 Australian Open|Australian Open]] as the heavy favorite to win the title; she was coming in with a 17-match winning streak that stretched from the [[2012 US Open (tennis)|2012 US Open]] and a 21-set winning streak stretching from the third set of the US Open final. In the first round, she faced [[Edina Gallovits-Hall]], where Williams suffered a health scare when she twisted her right ankle in the fifth game of the first set, however it did not hamper her as she won without dropping a game.<ref>{{cite web|work=Australian Open|title=Injured Serena puts on a clinic|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/articles/2013-01-15/201301151358220917746.html|date=15 January 2013|access-date=21 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016134007/http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/articles/2013-01-15/201301151358220917746.html|archive-date=16 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the next round she faced [[Garbi\u00f1e Muguruza]] and suffered another incident, when Williams's hit smacked her mouth with her racket following through on a defensive lob. Williams broke in the first game and also in the seventh game to win the first set; she then cruised through the second set with a [[bagel]].<ref>{{cite web|work=Australian Open|title=Williams passes Spanish test with ease|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/match_reports/2013-01-17/201301171358392594627.html|date=17 January 2013|access-date=21 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120052532/http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/match_reports/2013-01-17/201301171358392594627.html|archive-date=20 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the third round, against Japanese [[Ayumi Morita]], she served her second 207&nbsp;km/h serve of the tournament. Williams roared through the first set losing only one game, Morita then took the first three games, Williams then won the last six games to win the match.<ref>{{cite web|work=Australian Open|title=Serena serves it up|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/match_reports/2013-01-19/201301191358577063360.html|date=19 January 2013|access-date=21 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121232630/http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/match_reports/2013-01-19/201301191358577063360.html|archive-date=21 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Williams then faced 14th seed, Russia's [[Maria Kirilenko]]. Williams broke in the fourth and eighth games of the match to take the first set; she served 95% of first serve in the set. Williams stormed past the second set with a bagel to advance to the quarterfinals. Williams at one point won 23 straight service points. Williams also made 22 winners with 6 aces to Kirilenko's 7 winners with 1 ace, she also only made 6 unforced errors to Kirilenko's 15<ref>{{cite web|work=Australian Open|title=Serena muscles through|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/articles/2013-01-21/201301211358760774749.html|date=21 January 2013}}</ref> In the quarterfinals she faced compatriot [[Sloane Stephens]]; Williams took the first set by breaking in the eighth game. Williams then suffered a back spasm in the middle of the second set, where she led by a break but eventually lost the set 5\u20137. In the third set, Williams led by a break by the seventh game but eventually lost the next 3 games, losing to Stephens. Both women, made 23 winners; however, Williams made more unforced errors with 48 to Stephens 39. She also ended her 20-match winning streak and her 30 sets won in a row.<ref>{{cite web|work=Australian Open|title=Sloane stuns Serena|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/match_reports/2013-01-23/201301231358911885994.html|date=23 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nSerena Williams also played doubles with sister Venus. In the first three rounds, they faced [[Camila Giorgi]] and [[Stefanie V\u00f6gele]], [[Vera Dushevina]] and [[Olga Govortsova]],<ref>{{cite web|work=Australian Open|title=Williams doubles up|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/articles/2013-01-17/201301171358414536260.html|date=17 January 2013}}</ref> and fifth seeds [[Nadia Petrova]] and [[Katarina Srebotnik]] winning in straight sets in all three victories.<ref>{{cite web|work=Australian Open|title=Serena's double focus|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/articles/2013-01-20/201301201358670563189.html|date=17 January 2013}}</ref> In the quarterfinals, they faced top seeds [[Roberta Vinci]] and [[Sara Errani]], they took the first set and served for the match at 6\u20135, until they eventual lost the seconds set in a tie-break. They also had many chances in the third but lost it in the end 5\u20137.\n\n====Qatar Total Open====\n[[File:Serena Williams Doha 2013.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Serena Williams at the Doha press conference]]\n{{quote box|quote=\"I'm so sensitive nowadays, I'm always crying! I never thought I would be here again. I've just been through so much and never thought I'd be here again. Thank you Jehovah for giving me another chance.\"|source=Williams during her on court interview after defeating Kvitova and reclaiming the world no.1 status.<ref>http://www.wtatennis.com/news/article/3077656/title/warrior-serena-makes-history-in-doha</ref>|width=21%|align=right}}Williams then played at the [[2013 Qatar Total Open|Qatar Total Open]] in Doha for the first time. Williams, being seeded second, received a bye in the first round. In the second round, she faced a lucky loser in Russian [[Daria Gavrilova]]. Williams from the fifth game racked in nine straight games, Williams served out the match, she hit 25 winners to Gavrilova's 9, and both hit 14 unforced errors.<ref>{{cite web|work=WTA|title=SHARAPOVA STILL PERFECT, SERENA WINS TOO |url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/article/3073989/title/sharapova-still-perfect-serena-wins-too|date=12 February 2013}}</ref> In the second round she faced the younger Radwa\u0144ska [[Urszula Radwa\u0144ska|Urszula]], Williams won the first eight games, before being broken by Radwa\u0144ska. Williams closed it out in the ninth game of the second set. Williams had a 20\u201315 winner-unforced error to Radwa\u0144ska's 6\u201320.<ref>{{cite web|work=WTA|title=KVITOVA STANDS BETWEEN SERENA & NO.1 |url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/article/3076371/title/kvitova-stands-between-serena-no1|date=14 February 2013}}</ref> In the quarterfinals she faced world no. 8 [[Petra Kvitov\u00e1]], Kvitov\u00e1 took the first break in the sixth game and took advantage, winning the set, the first set Williams has lost to Kvitov\u00e1. The second set went Williams' favor as she broke in the eighth game closed it out. In the deciding set Kvitov\u00e1 took a break lead by the fifth game. However Williams came back to win the set 7\u20135. Williams made 14 aces to Kvitov\u00e1's 9, both served 8 double faults. Williams made 37 winners to Kvitov\u00e1's 35, but she also made more unforced errors 31 to 28. This win gave Williams the WTA number 1 ranking, becoming the oldest to hold it.<ref>{{cite web|work=WTA|title=WARRIOR SERENA MAKES HISTORY IN DOHA |url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/article/3077656/title/warrior-serena-makes-history-in-doha|date=15 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena Williams beats Kvitova in Qatar Open quarters, returns to No. 1|url=https://thestarphoenix.com/sports/Serena+Williams+beats+Kvitova+Qatar+Open+quarters+returns/7973951/story.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130412001444/http://www.thestarphoenix.com/sports/Serena+Williams+beats+Kvitova+Qatar+Open+quarters+returns/7973951/story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 April 2013|date=15 February 2013}}</ref> In the semifinals, Williams faced world no. 3 [[Maria Sharapova]]. Williams took the first set after breaking in the sixth game. Williams then dominated the second set, breaking the Russian twice to win it.<ref>{{cite web|work=WTA|title=VIKA VS SERENA: DREAM FINAL IN DOHA|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/article/3078567/title/vika-vs-serena-dream-final-in-doha|date=15 February 2013}}</ref> In the final, Williams faced the top seed [[Victoria Azarenka]], Williams went down by a break, but came back, eventually lead to a tie-break. Williams had set point on serve at 6\u20135, but lost the next three points to lose the breaker. Williams then took control of the second set winning it with two breaks. In the third set, Williams started slowly, losing the first three games, and it was enough for Azarenka as they both held serve until the end of the match. This loss was the first to Azarenka since the [[2009 Sony Ericsson Open]] and ended Williams' 9-match winning streak against Azarenka.<ref>{{cite web|work=WTA|title=AZARENKA MAKES BIG STATEMENT IN DOHA|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/article/3079596/title/azarenka-makes-big-statement-in-doha|date=15 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Dubai Tennis Championships====\nWilliams withdrew 45 minutes before she was due to play [[Marion Bartoli]] at the [[2013 Dubai Tennis Championships|Dubai Tennis Championships]] with a back injury.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena withdraws from Dubai with back injury|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/tennis/2013/02/20/serena-williams-back-injury-dubai-championships/1932453/|date=20 February 2013}}</ref> This withdrawal will count as a zero-pointer in her allotted year-end rankings.\n\n====Sony Open Tennis====\nPlaying in her first tournament as the world no. 1 at the [[2013 Sony Open Tennis|Sony Open Tennis]] as the top seed she received a bye into the second round where she faced Italian [[Flavia Pennetta]]. Williams took the first set with a loss of one game; she come back from triple break point down twice and she was 2/10 in break point opportunities. The second set was won by Williams by the same score.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Reuters|title=Tennis \u2013 Serena Williams blasts past Pennetta in Miami|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/tennis-serena-williams-blasts-past-pennetta-miami-195804989.html|date=22 March 2013}}</ref> Williams then took on [[Ayumi Morita]], Morita took the first 3 games of the match, but Williams pegged back taking the next 7 games, Williams then broke Morita in the sixth game of the second set to take the match.<ref>{{cite web|work=Sony Open Tennis|title=SERENA BEATS MORITA; KVITOVA OUSTED|url=http://www.sonyopentennis.com/News/Tennis/2013/Tournament/WTA-Saturday-Serena.aspx|date=23 March 2013}}</ref> In the fourth round, she faced Slovakian [[Dominika Cibulkov\u00e1]], the match started with 2 breaks, Cibulkov\u00e1 then took the next seven games from the fourth game, to take a set and break lead. Williams then took the next six games from, in the process winning the second set. Williams then completed her comeback, winning the third by 2. Williams ended with 40\u201341 winners-unforced errors to her opponents 12\u201319 ratio.<ref>{{cite web|work=Sports Illustrated|title=Serena Williams rallies for 3-set win at Sony Open|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/tennis/news/20130325/serena-williams-sony-open.ap/|date=26 March 2013}}</ref> In the quarterfinals, Williams faced [[Li Na]]. Williams took the first set breaking Li in the sixth game of the match. In the second set Williams took a break lead but Li took the next five games and had a set point on the Williams serve, Williams saved the set point and took the next four games to force a tie-break, that went to Williams.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena Williams beats Li to reach Miami semifinals|url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2013/03/serena-williams-beats-li-reach-miami-semifinals/46905/|date=26 March 2013}}</ref> In the semifinals, she faced fourth seed and defending champion [[Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska]]. Williams took the first set without dropping a game. In the second set Williams broke Radwa\u0144ska in the third game to finally take the set and the match. She hit 40 winners and 21 unforced errors to Radwa\u0144ska's 6 winners and 12 unforced errors. Williams made 12 aces including 5 in the third game of the second set.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena beats Radwanska to set up Miami final with Sharapova |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/serena-beats-radwanska-to-set-up-miami-final-with-sharapova/381806-5-22.html|date=28 March 2013}}</ref> In the final Williams faced [[Maria Sharapova]]. Sharapova got the decisive break in the ninth game and serve the set out. This ended the 13 straight sets Williams had won over Sharapova and the first she had lost in 5 years. In the second set, Williams won the first two games before Sharapova reeled off three straight games herself. Being a break down Williams reeled off 10 straight games to win the match. Williams had a 34\u201329 winners-to-unforced errors ratio to Sharapova's 14\u201325. This win gave Williams the most titles at the tournament at six and most wins at the event at 61 and is tied with Agassi in both accolades. This win also meant that Williams has beaten Sharapova 11 straight times.<ref>{{cite web|work=Sony Open Tennis|title=SERENA BEATS SHARAPOVA TO WIN RECORD SIXTH MIAMI TITLE |url=http://www.sonyopentennis.com/News/Tennis/2013/Tournament/WTA-Final-Serena-Wins-Record-Title.aspx|date=30 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena Williams beats Sharapova, wins Sony Open final|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/tennis/news/20130330/serena-williams-wins-title-sony-open-final.ap/|date=30 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Clay court season and French Open===\n\n====Family Circle Cup====\nWilliams then played her first clay court tournament at the [[2013 Family Circle Cup|Family Circle Cup]]. She entered the event as the defending champion and as the first seed. Williams received a bye to go through the second round, where she faced [[Camila Giorgi]]. Williams won the first set with Giorgi breaking and winning serve only once. In the second set, Williams broke in the fifth game and ninth game of the match to advance. Williams made nine aces and no double faults, whereas her opponent made five aces to a dozen double faults.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena Williams makes transition to clay with win |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/tennis/2013/04/02/serena-williams-family-circle-cup/2047497/|date=2 April 2013}}</ref> On the following day, she faced compatriot [[Mallory Burdette]], the first set went on serve until Williams broke in the tenth game to take the set. Williams then got broken in the first game, but came back winning six of the last seven games to win.<ref>{{cite web|work=ESPN|title=Serena advances in Charleston|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/tennis/sport/story/200940.html#|date=5 April 2013}}</ref> Later in the day Williams played her quarterfinal match, playing two singles match in the same for the first time in her career. Williams took on [[Lucie \u0160af\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1]] in a rematch of last year's final. The match began with two breaks, \u0160af\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1 then broke in the fifth game and then consolidated the break. However, Williams came back winning 10 of the last 11 games to go through.<ref>{{cite web|work=CBS|title=Williams sisters advance into semis|url=http://www.cbssports.com/tennis/story/22015149/williams-sisters-advance-into-semis|date=5 April 2013}}</ref> In the semifinals Williams faced big sister [[Venus Williams]] in their 24 meeting and their first in more than three years, with their last match coming in the [[2009 WTA Tour Championships]] Final. The first set went to Serena, with Serena breaking Venus thrice in the set, with she her herself getting broken once. In the second set, Serena broke Venus' serve in the first and seventh game to advance to the final. The match was the fewest games won by the losing foe with three in the all of the 24 meeting between the sisters.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena beats Venus in under an hour to reach Charleston final|url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2013/04/serena-beats-venus-under-hour-reach-charleston-final/47008/|date=6 April 2013}}</ref> In the final, Williams faced [[Jelena Jankovi\u0107]], whom she had led 5\u20134 in head-to-head. The first set, four games stayed on serve with Williams not dropping a point and Jankovi\u0107 being pushed to deuce. However, things turned around as Jankovi\u0107 broke Williams in the fifth and ninth game to take the set. The second set saw Williams rallied to take all of the six games to win it with a bagel. The third set went to Williams breaking Jankovi\u0107 in the third and seventh game and served out the match in her third match point. Williams was 39\u201325 winners to unforced errors to Jankovi\u0107 21\u201323. This is Williams third Family Circle Cup and extends her 15-match winning streak at the event.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena defeats Jankovic, wins 2nd straight Family Circle Cup|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/tennis/news/20130407/serena-williams-family-circle-cup.ap/?xid=si_topstories|date=7 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Mutua Madrid Open====\n[[File:Serena Williams Madrid 2013.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Serena Williams at the Mutua Madrid Open.]]\nWilliams came into the [[2013 Mutua Madrid Open|Mutua Madrid Open]] as the defending champion. Williams began her defense against [[Yulia Putintseva]]. Putintseva broke Williams in the opening game; Williams then broke back in the sixth game. The opening set then went to a tie-break, with Williams winning it. In the second set, Williams broke serve four times, while getting broken once herself to win the second set with a [[breadstick]] to win the match.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=S. Williams tops Putintseva in Madrid Open|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/tennis/s-williams-tops-putintseva-in-madrid-open/|date=5 May 2013}}</ref> In the following round, Williams went against local [[Lourdes Dom\u00ednguez Lino]]. Williams took an early lead in the first set and served for it in the seventh game just to be broken, but broke back to take the set. In the second set, they went toe-to-toe, where Williams sneaked ahead, breaking in the twelfth game to win the match.<ref>{{cite web|work=MSN|title=Serena sees off Dominguez Lino in Madrid|url=http://sport.uk.msn.com/tennis/serena-sees-off-dominguez-lino-in-madrid|date=8 May 2013|access-date=11 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102213534/http://sport.uk.msn.com/tennis/serena-sees-off-dominguez-lino-in-madrid|archive-date=2 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the round of 16, Williams faced 13th seed [[Maria Kirilenko]]. Both held serves in the first six games, until Williams raced through, winning nine of the last ten games. Williams made 22 winners and 10 unforced errors to Kirilenko's 9 and 25. Williams lost 2 points on serve, both on the second serve, and made no unforced errors in the second set.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=SWilliams, Sharapova win to reach Madrid quarters|url=https://news.yahoo.com/swilliams-sharapova-win-reach-madrid-quarters-124235661.html|date=9 May 2013}}</ref> In the last 8, Williams took on wild card [[Anabel Medina Garrigues]]; the first set went on serve until Williams broke in the eighth game and then served it out. In the second set, Medina Garrigues took advantage of an erratic Williams taking the second set in a [[bagel]]. Williams took the first two games of the final set just to see Medina Garrigues take the next four; however, Williams came back and won the set in the twelfth game. Williams made 39 winners to 48 unforced errors to Medina Garrigues' 19 and 18.<ref>{{cite web|work=Fox News|title=Serena Williams squeaks by Medina Garrigues in 3 sets to reach Madrid Open semifinals|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2013/05/10/serena-williams-squeaks-by-medina-garrigues-in-3-sets-to-reach-madrid-open/|date=10 May 2013}}</ref> In the semifinals, Williams faced [[Sara Errani]]. Errani broke twice in the third and seventh game just to see Williams break back right after. Williams then broke in a hard-fought game in the twelfth game to take the set. Williams then broke Errani in the fourth game and then in the eighth game to advance to the final. Williams made 47 winners to Errani's 8 and 39 unforced errors to Errani's 13. This marks Williams first red clay final since her triumph in the [[2002 French Open]].<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena Williams beats Errani to reach Madrid final|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/serena-williams-beats-errani-reach-110844877--ten.html|date=11 May 2013}}</ref> Williams faced 2nd-seed [[Maria Sharapova]] in the final, where the winner could take the number 1 ranking. Williams dominated the first set, winning the first four games and eventually closing it out in the seventh game. Sharapova then broke Williams in the opening game but Williams broke back in sixth game and then again in the tenth game to take the match. Williams made 18 winners and unforced errors, while Sharapova made 14 winners to 21 unforced errors. This is Williams' 50th career title and her first on the red clay since the [[2002 French Open]].<ref>{{cite web|work=BBC|title=Serena Williams beats Maria Sharapova in Madrid Open final|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/22501208|date=12 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Internazionali BNL d'Italia====\nWilliams came into the [[2013 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Internazionali BNL d'Italia]] with a 19-match winning streak and the top seed. She received a bye into the round of 16 and played British number 1 [[Laura Robson]]. The match began with Robson breaking Williams; however Williams won 6 of the next 7 games to take the set. Williams then broke serve twice to take a similar scoreline and advance. Williams was 13-11 winners-unforced errors to Robson 16-35.<ref>{{cite web|work=BBC|title=Laura Robson loses to Serena Williams in Italian Open|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/22533961|date=14 May 2013}}</ref> In the next round she took on [[Dominika Cibulkov\u00e1]] and dropped only a game in the match and made 40 winners to 16 unforced errors.<ref>{{cite web|work=ESPN|title=Super Serena slays Cibulkova in Rome|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/tennis/sport/story/207555.html#|date=16 May 2013}}</ref> In the final 8, Williams faced [[Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro]]. Williams took control of the match losing only two games both in the first set. Williams made 26 winners to 14 unforced errors to the Spaniards 9 winners and 16 unforced errors.<ref>{{cite web|work=Sports Direct|title=Serena Williams sails through QF|url=http://www.sportsdirectnews.com/tennis/24678-serena-williams-sails-through-qf.php|date=17 May 2013}}</ref> In the semifinals, Williams went against surprise semifinalist in qualifier [[Simona Halep]]. Halep took an early break in the third game, however Williams came back winning 11 of the last 12 games, including a bagel in the second set to win the match. Williams made 24 winners and 20 unforced errors to Halep's 3 and 17.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena wins 23rd straight in Rome semis over Halep|url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2013/05/serena-drops-just-three-games-halep-rome-semis/47497/|date=18 May 2013}}</ref> In the final she faced [[Victoria Azarenka]] in a rematch of the Doha final. Williams took the first three games before Azarenka could take a game breaking Williams' serve in the fourth game, Williams then took the next three to win the set. The pair then traded three breaks of serve from the sixth game, before Williams could serve it out in the ninth game and revenge her loss. Williams hit 41 winners and 19 unforced errors in the match along with 8 aces. The win extends Williams longest winning streak in her career to 24.<ref>{{cite web|work=Fox News|title=Serena extends career-best run, wins Rome title|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2013/05/19/serena-extends-career-best-run-wins-rome-title/|date=19 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n====French Open====\n[[File:Serena Williams - Roland-Garros 2013 - 013.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Serena Williams at the French Open against Caroline Garcia.]]\nWilliams came into the [[2013 French Open|French Open]] as the favorite, having not lost a match on clay and riding on a 24 match winning streak. Williams also was the top seed and world no. 1 and will come out of the event as the world no. 1 whatever the result of the tournament is.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Nadal, Serena Williams heavy favorites at French Open|url=http://www.timesdispatch.com/sports/professional/tennis/article_5cf80794-1d3f-5a49-b8db-4c3a3d45c0f2.html|date=24 May 2013}}</ref> In her opening match, she went up against [[Anna Tatishvili]], where Williams rallied through to win the first nine games dropping only a point on serve before Tatishvili could get a game. Williams then won the remaining three games to advance.<ref>{{cite web|work=Bleacher|title=Serena Williams Defeats Anna Tatishvili to Advance at 2013 French Open|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1652128-serena-williams-defeats-anna-tatishvili-to-advance-at-2013-french-open|date=26 May 2013}}</ref> In the next round, Williams faced wildcard [[Caroline Garcia]]. Williams won the first five games and finished it off the set in the seventh game and then broke twice in the second to take the match. Williams made 27 winners and 9 unforced errors to her opponents 14 a piece.<ref>{{cite web|work=Sky Sports|title=French Open: Serena Williams easily sees off Caroline Garcia in second round|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2013/05/19/serena-extends-career-best-run-wins-rome-title/|date=30 May 2013}}</ref> In the third round, Williams took on [[Sorana C\u00eerstea]]. Williams took the first set in a bagel, the second set went on serve until the fifth game, where Williams won the last four games. Williams was 13-16 on winners and unforced errors.<ref>{{cite web|work=Chicago Tribune|title=Serena Williams defeats Cirstea to advance in Paris|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-05-31/sports/sns-rt-us-tennis-open-serenabre94u0r7-20130531_1_serena-williams-next-round-winning-streak|date=31 May 2013}}</ref> In the round of 16, Williams went against the no. 1 doubles player [[Roberta Vinci]], Williams took the first set, dropping only a game. The second set went on serve until Williams broke in the eighth game and closed it out in the next game to win in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|work=Yahoo|title=Serena Williams beats Vinci in 4th round at French|url=https://news.yahoo.com/serena-williams-beats-vinci-4th-round-french-131705293.html|date=2 June 2013}}</ref> In the quarterfinals, Williams faced former French Open champion [[Svetlana Kuznetsova]]. In the first set, Williams cruised through the set dropping only a game with the aid of 15 winners. However, in the second set, Kuznetsova won the first four games. Kuznetsova then served for the set in the ninth game and was up 40-0, however Williams squandered four break points in the game to bring it to a deciding set. Kuznetsova hit 11 winners to Williams' 8, while hitting the same number of unforced errors. Kuznetsova then broke early and had a chance to take a second break in the 3rd game, however Williams saved three break points to hold. Williams then won 5 of the last 6 game to advance to her first French Open semifinal since 2003.<ref>{{cite web|work=Telegraph|title=French Open 2013: Serena Williams forced to fight back against Svetlana Kuznetsova to claim place in semi-finals|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/frenchopen/10098983/French-Open-2013-Serena-Williams-forced-to-fight-back-against-Svetlana-Kuznetsova-to-claim-place-in-semi-finals.html|date=4 June 2013}}</ref> In the semifinals, Williams faced last years runner-up [[Sara Errani]]. Williams stormed through the first 9 games before Errani could get her only game of the match. Williams then served it out in the seventh game in a 46-minute white wash, dropping only 5 points on serve. Williams hit 40 winners to her opponents 2 and 15 unforced errors to Errani's 3.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena Williams beats Sara Errani at French Open|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/tennis/news/20130606/serena-williams-sara-errani-french-open.ap/|date=6 June 2013}}</ref> [[Chris Evert]] described this as the finest female performance on clay she had ever seen.<ref>{{cite web|last=Caple|first=Jim|title=New Heights For Serena Williams|url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/9352085/2013-french-open-serena-williams-looks-better-ever-heading-final-maria-sharapova|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=June 7, 2013}}</ref> Williams faced defending champion and number 2 seed [[Maria Sharapova]] in the final. Williams was broken in the second game, but won four of the next five games to gain the lead. Sharapova then broke back in the eight game before Williams went on to break again to take the set in the tenth game. Williams proceeded to play well breaking Sharapova's serve in the second set before serving for the championship in the tenth game. In this service game, Williams fired 3 aces to win her second French Open title 11 years after her first. Williams hit 29 winners-21 unforced errors-10 aces-0 double faults to Sharapova's 10-17-2-4 in comparison. The win improved Williams' win-streak to a career-longest 31 matches.<ref>{{cite web|work=BBC|title=French Open: Serena Williams beats Maria Sharapova to win title|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/22812732|accessdate=June 8, 2013}}</ref> She became the fourth woman in the Open era after [[Martina Navratilova]], [[Chris Evert]] and [[Steffi Graf]] to win each Grand Slam title twice or more.\n\n===Wimbledon===\nWilliams came into [[2013 Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] as the heavy favorite to win her sixth Wimbledon title, being on a 31-match winning streak, number 1 seed, and defending champion. Williams opened her campaign for her 17th slam against [[Mandy Minella]]. Williams stormed through the first set dropping only a game and not dropping a point on serve. Minella then came back, winning the first two games of the second set, just to see Williams reel off six of the last seven games to win.<ref>{{cite web|work=DailyMail|title=Williams in devastating form as favourite destroys hapless Minella in straight sets|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/tennis/article-2348128/Wimbledon-2013-Serena-Williams-beats-Mandy-Minella.html|date=25 June 2013}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}} In the next round, she took on youngster [[Caroline Garcia]], Williams took the first set by breaking Garcia in the ninth game, then took the second set taking the last four games from 2-all.<ref>{{cite web|work=DailyMail|title=As others fall, top seed Serena marches on with dominant straight sets victory|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/tennis/article-2349753/Wimbledon-2013-Serena-Williams-beats-Caroline-Garcia-6-3-6-2-round-two.html|date=27 June 2013}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}} In the round of 32, Williams faced Japanese veteran [[Kimiko Date-Krumm]]. Williams served for the first set in the seventh game, just to get broken. But Williams came back to take the next seven games to win in two sets.<ref>{{cite web|work=Bleacher Report|title=Serena Williams Defeats Kimiko Date-Krumm to Advance at 2013 Wimbledon|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1688926-serena-williams-defeats-kimiko-date-krumm-to-advance-at-2013-wimbledon|date=29 June 2013}}</ref> In the last 16, Williams had German [[Sabine Lisicki]] in her path. Lisicki took the first set at ease dropping only two games as Williams fired back in the second set dropping only a game. Williams then took a 3-0 lead then a 4-2 lead, however Williams got passive, wasting four break points in the 8th game as Lisicki took initiative and took four games in a row to win 6-4 in the third, ending Williams's 34-match winning streak, the longest in her career.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena Williams Loses To Sabine Lisicki In Wimbledon 4th Round|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/01/serena-williams-lisicki-wimbledon-4th-round-upset_n_3528668.html|date=1 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Collector Swedish Open====\nAfter her Wimbledon Loss, Williams came back to clay and played the [[2013 Swedish Open|Collector Swedish Open]]. Williams played her opening match against [[Sesil Karatantcheva]]. Williams won the match with ease dropping only three games in just 64 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|work=Eurosport|title=Serena too strong for Karatantcheva in Bastad|url=http://eurosport.du.ae/tennis/serena-too-strong-for-karatantcheva-in-bastad_sto3845667/story.shtml|date=16 July 2013|access-date=2 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227113013/http://eurosport.du.ae/tennis/serena-too-strong-for-karatantcheva-in-bastad_sto3845667/story.shtml|archive-date=27 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In her second round match, Williams took on [[Anna Tatishvili]], Williams cruised to victory in straight sets with help from her seven aces.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena beats Tatishvili, into Bastad quarters|url=http://www.supersport.com/tennis/wta/news/130718/Serena_beats_Tatishvili_into_Bastad_quarters|date=18 July 2013}}</ref> Williams then faced Spaniard [[Lourdes Dom\u00ednguez Lino]], demolishing her opponent, Williams won in a double breadstick scoreline.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena breaks Dominguez Lino six times, loses two games in quarterfinal win|url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2013/07/serena-breaks-dominguez-lino-six-times-loses-two-games-quarterfinal-win/48432/|date=19 July 2013}}</ref> In the final four, Williams had [[Kl\u00e1ra Zakopalov\u00e1]] on the other side of the net. Williams dominated the opening, proceeding to take the first 8 games of the match. Zakopalov\u00e1 came back and broke Williams to get on serve up to the 8th game; however, Williams took the last 2 games to reach the final.<ref>{{cite web|work=GlobeandMail|title=Serena defeats Zakopalova to earn spot in Swedish Open final|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/more-sports/serena-defeats-zakopalova-to-earn-spot-in-swedish-open-final/article13331774/|date=20 July 2013}}</ref> In the final, Williams took on local [[Johanna Larsson (tennis)|Johanna Larsson]]. Larsson took an early break lead, breaking Williams in the 4th game, just to see Williams reel in 11 of the next 13 games to win the title. This is Williams' first title that is below a premier level. This also marks Williams being undefeated on clay in 2013 having a 28-0 record.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Canadian Press|title=SERENA WILLIAMS BEATS LARSSON TO WIN SWEDISH OPEN|url=https://www.tsn.ca/tennis/story/?id=428118|date=21 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===US Open Series===\n\n====Rogers Cup====\nWilliams' began her US Open campaign at the [[2013 Rogers Cup]] in Toronto. Williams received a bye in the first round and faced [[Francesca Schiavone]]. Schiavone broke in the fifth game; however, Williams came back and won seven games in a row to take a set and double break lead. Schiavone then took two games just to see Williams take the next two and win the match.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Agence France-Presse|title=Serena Williams defeats Francesca Schiavone in Toronto opener|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/tennis/news/212038-serena-williams-defeats-francesca-schiavone-in-toronto-opener|date=8 August 2013|access-date=27 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811192029/http://sports.ndtv.com/tennis/news/212038-serena-williams-defeats-francesca-schiavone-in-toronto-opener|archive-date=11 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the third round, Williams faced Venus' conqueror [[Kirsten Flipkens]]. Williams dominated the first set with a bagel. In the second set, Williams broke in the fourth game and it was enough to take the set and advance.<ref>{{cite web|work=BBC|title=Serena Williams thrashes Kirsten Flipkens in Rogers Cup|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/23627439|date=9 August 2013}}</ref> In the quarterfinals, Williams defeated Slovakian [[Magdal\u00e9na Ryb\u00e1rikov\u00e1]], dropping only a game on each set, which was a hold and a break respectively.<ref>{{cite web|work=Sportsmole|title=Result: Serena Williams cruises past Magdalena Rybarikova|url=http://www.sportsmole.co.uk/tennis/rogers-cup/result/result-williams-cruises-past-rybarikova_97743.html|date=10 August 2013}}</ref> In the final 4, Williams took on [[Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska]]. In the first set, the pair traded breaks twice to push it to a tiebreak, which Williams won. In the second set, Radwa\u0144ska took an early break lead, however Williams then broke Radwa\u0144ska twice to win the match.<ref>{{cite web|work=Associated Foreign Press|title=Serena Williams powers into Toronto final|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-08-11/top-stories/41294367_1_serena-williams-match-point-li-na|date=11 August 2013}}</ref> Williams then took on surprise finalist [[Sorana C\u00eerstea]]; Williams took the first three games, just to see C\u00eerstea take the next two, however Williams raced through winning the last nine games to win the title. This is Williams' eight title of the year matching her most titles in a year.<ref>{{cite web|work=meniscus|title=Serena Williams wins 2013 Rogers Cup in Toronto|url=http://www.meniscuszine.com/articles/2013082424957/serena-williams-wins-third-rogers-cup-in-toronto/|date=24 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Western & Southern Open====\nAfter a successful campaign at the Roger's Cup in Toronto, Williams played in the [[2013 Western & Southern Open]] in [[Cincinnati]]. Although she came in as the clear favorite, Williams had never won the tournament before. Along with the other top 8 seeds, she received a first round bye and went on to face [[Eugenie Bouchard]] of Canada in the second round. Bouchard broke in the first game, they then traded breaks in the fourth and fifth game. Bouchard then held with a break lead in the tenth game to take the set. Williams then broke in the fourth and eight game to push it to a decider. In the third set, Williams took the first four games, before Bouchard could take two straight games to see Williams win the next two to advance.<ref>{{cite web|work=ESPN|title=Williams rallies to see off Bouchard|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/tennis/sport/story/230131.html|date=14 August 2013}}</ref> Williams then took on German [[Mona Barthel]]. Williams broke in the second game, just to be broken serving for the set in the ninth game, however Williams broke to take the set. Williams then won the first five games before Barthel could win a game; Williams then closed it out to win.<ref>{{cite web|work=Sporting life|title=Serena Williams defeats Barthel|url=http://www.sportinglife.com/tennis/news/article/553/8872539/serena-williams-defeats-barthel|date=16 August 2013}}</ref> In the quarterfinals, Williams faced [[Simona Halep]] and took the first set with a bagel. The second set was closer; the pair traded breaks in the fourth and fifth game before Williams could break in the tenth game to win the match.<ref>{{cite web|work=BBC|title=Serena Williams beats Simona Halep to reach Cincinnati semi|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/23735974|date=17 August 2013}}</ref> Williams then went against China's [[Li Na]] and won in straight sets. The two sets had similar situations as Williams took a 4-2 lead in both; Li served for both in the tenth game just to get broken by Williams and then again in the twelfth game of each set to reach her first Cincinnati final.<ref>{{cite web|work=Cincinnati.com|title=Williams downs Li Na to reach finals|url=http://news.cincinnati.com/article/20130817/SPT/308170092/Williams-downs-Li-Na-reach-finals?nclick_check=1|date=17 August 2013}}</ref> The final saw the top two seeds, Williams and Azarenka, take to the court for the title. After a dominant display by Williams and an error plagued game from Azarenka, Williams took the first set with a two break lead. A revitalised Azarenka began to take charge and the errors started creeping into Williams game, Azarenka then took the second set with a similar scoreline. Azarenka led by an early break in the final set, just to see Williams come back and serve for it in the tenth game only to get broken and lead to a tie-break, which Azarenka took 8 points to 6. This broke Williams' 14 match winning streak.<ref>{{cite web|work=BBC|title=Victoria Azarenka beats Serena Williams in Cincinnati Open final|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/23750672|date=19 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n====US Open====\n[[File:Serena Williams (9634013070).jpg|thumb|left|160px|Serena Williams at the US Open.]]\nAfter her disappointing loss to Azarenka in Cincinnati, Serena entered the 2013 [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] as the top seed, the defending champion, and bidding to become the oldest woman to win the U.S. Open since tennis turned professional in 1968.  She beat former [[French Open]] champion [[Francesca Schiavone]] in the opening round, dropping only a game and hitting 13 winners to 8 unforced errors.<ref>{{cite web|work=DailyMail|title=Williams sends Schiavone packing at US Open as favourite cruises into second round|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/tennis/article-2402510/US-OPEN-2013-Serena-Williams-beats-Francesca-Schiavone.html|date=27 August 2013}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}} In the second and third rounds, Williams easily dispatched Kazakhstan opponents, [[Galina Voskoboeva]] and [[Yaroslava Shvedova]].<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena Williams steamrolls over Galina Voskoboeva en route to U.S. Open third round|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more-sports/serena-steamrolls-open-article-1.1440719|date=29 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=The Guardian|title=Serena Williams beats Yaroslava Shvedova to set up Sloane Stephens tie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/aug/31/serena-williams-sloane-stephens-us-open|date=31 August 2013}}</ref> In the Round of 16, Williams had a rematch of the Australian Open against [[Sloane Stephens]], who surprisingly beat Williams in that event. In the first set, Williams broke first only to get broken back by Stephens in the 7th game. Williams then broke in the tenth game to take the set and cruised through the second set in a breadstick to avenge her loss at the Australian Open. Williams put up a ratio of 22 winners to 13 unforced errors.<ref>{{cite web|work=Sports Illustrated|title=Serena proves it's not Sloane Stephens' time yet|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/tennis/news/20130901/serena-williams-sloane-stephens-us-open/|date=31 August 2013}}</ref> She then faced [[Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro]], in the latter's birthday. Williams didn't drop a game, handing the Spaniard a double bagel loss; the first in a US Open since 1989, when 18-time major title winner [[Martina Navratilova]] did it to [[Manuela Maleeva]]. She again had a good ratio, with 20 winners to 9 unforced errors.<ref>{{cite web|work=ESPN|title=Serena Williams in semis after rout|url=http://espn.go.com/tennis/usopen13/story/_/id/9630551/2013-us-open-serena-williams-shuts-carla-suarez-navarro-make-semifinals|date=4 September 2013}}</ref> In the final 4, Williams faced 5th seeded [[Li Na]] of China. Williams cruised past the Chinese with a bagel in the first round. Li then took an early break in the second, but Williams won four straight games. Li then served to stay in the match in the 7th game and saved 6 match points to make Williams serve it out, which Williams did in her 7th match point. For the first time in the event, Williams made more unforced errors of 20 to winners of 19.<ref>{{cite web|work=USA Today|title=Serena vs. Azarenka: Bragging rights up for grabs|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/tennis/2013/09/07/us-open-2013-womens-final-serena-williams-victoria-azarenka/2779511/|date=7 September 2013}}</ref> In the final, Williams took on second seed [[Victoria Azarenka]] in a rematch of last year's final. The pair exchanged breaks in the first two games. Williams then survived a long tenth game and broke the Belarusian the following game, then served out the set. In the second set, Williams served for the match twice in the tenth and twelfth game, but got broken by Azarenka to push it to a tie-break, which Azarenka outlasted Williams 8-6. Williams then cruised through the final set dropping only a game, winning the match on her 2nd championship point. Williams made 36 winners and 9 aces to 35 unforced errors and 5 double faults. This was Williams' 5th US Open and 17th Slam title. It was the first time Serena was able to defend a US Open title while also becoming the oldest women's US Open champion in the [[Open Era]], surpassing the previous record set by Australia's [[Margaret Court]]. For winning the [[2013 US Open (tennis)|US Open Series]], Williams received $2.6m and an additional million in prize money, the highest single paycheck in tennis.<ref>{{cite web|work=USA Today|title=Serena Williams captures U.S. Open crown|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/tennis/2013/09/08/us-open-2013-serena-williams-victoria-azarenka-womens-final/2783547/|date=8 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=AFP|title=Live Report: US Open women's final|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/live-report-serena-azarenka-contest-us-open-title-193021793--ten.html|date=8 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=CNN|title=Serena Williams triumphs in U.S. Open at Flushing Meadows|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/09/08/sport/tennis/tennis-us-open-serena-azarenka/?hpt=hp_t3|date=9 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the doubles competition, Serena paired with sister [[Venus Williams|Venus]] for the second time in the year. They opened their US Open against the Spanish pairing of [[Silvia Soler Espinosa]] and [[Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro]]. They lost the first set in a tie-break but they dominated the next two sets, dropping just three games, with a bagel in the second. They then competed against compatriots, [[Raquel Kops-Jones]] and [[Abigail Spears]], and won both sets.<ref>{{cite web|work=Sports Illustrated|title=Williams sisters move on in doubles at U.S. Open|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/tennis/news/20130831/serena-williams-venus-williams-doubles-us-open.ap/|date=31 August 2013}}</ref> Next, they played [[Anastasia Pavlyuchenkova]] and [[Lucie \u0160af\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1]], and quickly dominated the first set with a breadstick. In the second set, they served for the match in the tenth game but got broken and were pushed to a tie-break, which they won.<ref>{{cite web|work=Tennis World USA|title=Williams sisters dismiss Lucie Safarova/Anatasia Pavlyuchenkova(11)|url=http://www.tennisworldusa.org/WTA-US-Open-Williams-sisters-dismiss-Lucie-Safarova-Anatasia-Pavlyuchenkova(11)-articolo12713.html|date=5 September 2013}}</ref> In the quarterfinals, they took on world no. 1's [[Sara Errani]] and [[Roberta Vinci]], and dominated them in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|work=LA Times|title=Venus and Serena Williams upset top-seeded Errani and Vinci|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-us-open-williams-sisters-20130905,0,5357918.story#axzz2fs2F9kmx|date=5 September 2013}}</ref> In the semifinals, the sisters faced the Czech pairing of [[Andrea Hlav\u00e1\u010dkov\u00e1]] and [[Lucie Hradeck\u00e1]], and were surprisingly beaten in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|work=Huffington Post|title=Williams Sisters Lose U.S. Open Women's Doubles Semifinals|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/06/williams-sisters-doubles-us-open_n_3883756.html|date=6 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Asian Swing and Year-End Championships===\n\n====China Open====\nWilliams came into the [[2013 China Open (tennis)|China Open]] as the top seed and was assured to end the year at number 1. Williams began her quest for her 10th title against [[Elena Vesnina]] in the first round. The first set saw Vesnina breaking Williams twice; However, Williams broke the Russian three times to take the set. Williams then won the last five games to advance.<ref>{{cite web|work=WTA|title=Serena Beats Vesnina, Praises Venus|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/article/3475421/title/serena-beats-vesnina-praises-venusl|date=29 September 2013}}</ref> In the second round, Williams took on [[Francesca Schiavone]], in a rematch of the US Open first round where Williams only dropped a game. In the first set, it remained on serve until the tenth game when Williams broke Schiavone to take the set. In the second set, Schiavone served for it in the ninth game and had 2 set points but Williams broke and took the next three games to win the set and match.<ref>{{cite web|work=ESPN|title=Williams withstands tough Schiavone test|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/tennis/sport/story/243317.html|date=1 October 2013}}</ref> Williams then faced [[Maria Kirilenko]] in the round of 16 and defeated her Russian opponent in two very tight sets, with Williams winning both sets by breaking Kirilenko in the twelfth game.<ref>{{cite web|work=AFP|title=Serena Williams stumbles through to last eight in China|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/serena-williams-stumbles-last-eight-china-072936241--ten.html|date=3 October 2013}}</ref> In the quarterfinals, Williams went against [[Caroline Wozniacki]]. Williams won 10 of the first 11 games in the process, taking the first set. However, Wozniacki came back winning three games in a row to keep it just a break down. Williams kept the break lead and won the second set.<ref>{{cite web|work=Eurosport|title=Tennis \u2013 Williams breezes past Wozniacki to reach China semis|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/tennis-serena-beats-wozniacki-straight-sets-140007917--ten.html|date=4 October 2013}}</ref> In the semifinals, she took on 3rd seed [[Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska]] and won in straight sets; breaking Radwa\u0144ska twice on each set and facing only 1 break point in the last game and saving it.<ref>{{cite web|work=DNA|title='Exasperated' Agnieszka Radwanska mulls 'playing left-handed' to beat 'invincible' Serena Williams!|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/1899152/report-exasperated-agnieszka-radwanska-mulls-playing-left-handed-to-beat-invincible-serena-williams|date=6 October 2013}}</ref> Williams then faced [[Jelena Jankovi\u0107]] in the final. In the first set, Williams broke Jankovi\u0107 twice to take the set. In the second set, Jankovi\u0107 broke in the third game, but took a medical timeout right after and lost the last five games to give Williams the title. This was Williams' 10th title of the year and her first China Open title since winning the first edition of the event in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|work=UPI|title=Serena Williams picks up 10th WTA title of 2013|url=http://www.upi.com/Sports_News/2013/10/06/Serena-Williams-picks-up-10th-WTA-title-of-2013/UPI-79271381066764/|date=6 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n====WTA Championships====\nWilliams came into the [[2013 WTA Tour Championships|Year-End Championships]] being assured to end the year at no. 1 and in a 10 match winning streak having won it in 2012 and 2009, while missing the 2010 and 2011 editions. She was grouped alongside [[Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska]], [[Petra Kvitov\u00e1]], and [[Angelique Kerber]] in the red group. Her first match was against German Kerber. Williams broke at the 3rd game of the first set and held serve in the entire set to take the first. Williams then won the second set with a breadstick. Williams made 31 winners and 11 unforced errors in the match.<ref>{{cite web|work=WTA Championships|title=Williams & Kvitova Make Winning Starts|url=http://www.wtachampionships.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12910~3506439,00.html|date=22 October 2013}}</ref> In her second match in her group, Williams faced Pole Radwa\u0144ska. Williams broke Radwa\u0144ska to wrap up both sets in the eight and tenth game respectively to go 2-0 in her group.<ref>{{cite web|work=BBC|title=Serena Williams beats Agnieszka Radwanska in Istanbul|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/24648452|date=23 October 2013}}</ref> In her final round robin match, she took on Czech Kvitov\u00e1. Williams fend off break points in the opening game and then broke Kvitov\u00e1 in the second and eight game to take a set lead and assured her a spot in the semifinals. The second set was tighter, Williams broke Kvitov\u00e1 in the fourth game and that was enough to win the set. Williams hit 11 aces in the match.<ref>{{cite web|work=Washington Post|title=Serena Williams beats Petra Kvitova to reach semifinals of WTA Championships|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/li-na-beats-jelena-jankovic-6-3-2-6-6-3-at-wta-championships/2013/10/24/782f490c-3ccd-11e3-b0e7-716179a2c2c7_story.html|date=25 October 2013}}</ref> After finishing first in her group, Williams took on [[Jelena Jankovi\u0107]] in the semifinals. Jankovi\u0107 took the initial lead breaking Williams in the fourth game, but Williams came back breaking the Serbian in the fifth and seventh game, and held in the tenth game to take the first set. In the second set, Jankovi\u0107 broke the American three times, whilst getting broken once to take the set breaking Williams in the eight game, this is the first set Williams lost in 11 consecutive straight set wins at the event. In the deciding set, the first 3 games were breaks of serve, Williams then broke against in the fifth game. Williams served for it for the first time at the eight game but was broken, however, she closed it out serving it out in the tenth game in her 4th match point and saving a break point. Williams hit an even 40 winners and 40 unforced errors.<ref>{{cite web|work=BBC|title=Serena Williams injured but beats Jelena Jankovic to reach final of WTA Championships in Istanbul|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/10406875/Serena-Williams-injured-but-beats-Jelena-Jankovic-to-reach-final-of-WTA-Championships-in-Istanbul.html|date=26 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=WTA Championships|title=Serena Employs Survival Tactics In Semis|url=http://www.wtachampionships.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12910~3512270,00.html|date=26 October 2013}}</ref> In the final, Williams took on first time finalist and fourth seed [[Li Na]]. Li dominated the first set breaking Williams twice to take the set. Williams took a quick lead in the second set taking the first three games, however Li came back winning the next three. However Williams dominated winning the final nine games, to take the sets at three and love to claim her fourth Year End Championships title and 11th title in the year. She also extends her winning streak at 15 at the event.<ref>{{cite web|work=Fox|title=Serena Williams wins WTA title|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/tennis/story/serena-williams-beats-li-na-to-win-wta-championships-her-11th-title-of-the-year-101713|date=28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=BBC|title=Serena Williams beats Li Na to win WTA Championships|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/24694991|date=27 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=WTA Championships|title=Superb Serena Defends Title|url=http://www.wtachampionships.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12910~3513229,00.html|date=27 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Fed Cup===\nWhile she didn't play in the United States' first round match against Italy, Williams represented [[United States Fed Cup team|United States]] in the [[2013 Fed Cup World Group Play-offs|Fed Cup]] against [[Sweden Fed Cup team|Sweden]] for a spot in the 2014 World Group. In her opening rubber, she faced [[Johanna Larsson (tennis)|Johanna Larsson]] and dominated her opponent winning both set with a loss of only two games in each in just 66 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Serena Williams pulls U.S. even|url=http://espn.go.com/tennis/story/_/id/9193550/serena-williams-overcomes-rain-johanna-larsson-even-united-states-sweden-fed-cup-play|date=21 April 2013}}</ref> In her second rubber, Williams took on [[Sofia Arvidsson]] and just needed 56 minutes to a straight set victory to give United States a 2-1 advantage, which her sister Venus closed out when she beat Larsson to help US advance to the World Group.<ref>{{cite web|work=Vanguard|title=Serena gives US lead over Sweden in Fed Cup|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2013/04/serena-gives-us-lead-over-sweden-in-fed-cup/l|date=21 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==All matches==\n\n===Singles matches===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold\"\n| style=\"width:300px;\"| Tournament\n| style=\"width:50px;\"| Match\n| style=\"width:50px;\"| Round\n| style=\"width:225px;\"| Opponent\n| style=\"width:50px;\"| Rank\n| style=\"width:50px;\"| Result\n| style=\"width:120px;\"| Score\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"background:#d4f1c5; text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| '''[[2013 Brisbane International|Brisbane International]]'''<br> [[Brisbane]], Australia<br>WTA Premier<br>Hard, outdoor<br>30 December 2012 \u2013 5 January 2013\n| 663\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| 1R\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Varvara Lepchenko]] \n| #21\n|bgcolor=lightgreen| Win\n| 6\u20132, 6\u20131\n|-\n| 664\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\" | 2R\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Aliz\u00e9 Cornet]] \n| #44\n|bgcolor=lightgreen